05110nam a22005895i 9780804768382DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222007cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047683827 a10.1515/97808047683822doi  a(DE-B1597)582096  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 7aLAW0960002bisacsh00aBench Press :bThe Collision of Courts, Politics, and the Media /ced. by Keith J. Bybee. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2022] 4cÂ©2007  a1 online resource (240 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aStanford Studies in Law and Politics00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Two Faces of Judicial Power -- tI Context -- t1 Preserving Public Confidence in the Courts in an Age of Individual Rights and Public Skepticism -- t2 Politicizing the Process: The New Politics of State Judicial Elections -- tII Views from the Bench -- t3 An Essay on Judicial Selection: A Brief History -- t4 Judicial Independence: The Courts and the Media -- t5 Politics and the Confirmation Process: Thoughts on the Roberts and Alito Hearings -- t6 Selecting the Judiciary: Who Should Be the Judge? -- tIII Views from the Media -- t7 Winners and Losers -- t8 The Internet and the Judiciary: We Are All Experts Now -- t9 The Distance between Judges and Journalists -- tAfterword: The State of Judicial Independence -- tContributors -- tCited Authorities -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFederal court confirmations in the United States have become openly political affairs, with partisans lining up to support their preferred candidates. Matters in the states are not much different, with once sleepy judicial elections changing into ever more contentious political slugfests, replete with single-issue interest groups and negative campaign advertising. Once on the bench, judges at every level find themselves dogged by charges of politically motivated decision-making. In this first-of-its-kind collection, prominent figures from the academy, the bench, and the press reflect on the state of the American judiciary. Using the results of a specially commissioned public opinion poll as a starting point, the contributors examine the complex mix of legal principle, political maneuvering, and press coverage that swirl around judicial selection and judicial decision making today. Essays examine the rise of explicitly political state judicial elections, the merits of judicial appointments, the rhetoric of federal judicial confirmation hearings, the quality of legal reporting, the portrayal of courts on the Internet, the inevitable tensions between judges and journalists, and the importance of regulating judicial appearances. Contributors Include: Keith J. Bybee, Charles Gardner Geyh, G. Alan Tarr, Harold See, James E. Graves, Jr., John M. Walker, Jr., Joanne F. Alper, Mark Obbie, Dahlia Lithwick, Tom Goldstein, and Anthony Lewis  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aPolitics -- Judicial Politics. 4aPolitics -- United States. 7aLAW / Media & the Law.2bisacsh1 aAlper, Joanne F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBybee, Keith J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBybee, Keith J., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGeyh, Charles Gardner, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldstein, Tom, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGraves, Jr., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLewis, Anthony, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLithwick, Dahlia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca